Continuing mega found on 10/30 and hosted by Beth Tiller. 2nd record of Anna's Hummingbird for Dakota County.   Immature male hummingbird. Rose-pink gorget and crown feathers sparse but visible. Light gray underparts with green speckles. Irridescent green flanks and slightly more bluish-green back. Green nape. Black wings with slight deep purple undertones. Tail feathers I observed were black, but I did not observe the spread tail as Beth did on 10/30. Tail extended past wingtips. Bill was quite straight and short compared to other hummingbirds I have observed.  RTHU, BCHU, and all Selasphorus sp. that occur in the ABA area are ruled out due to the presence of rose-pink feathers (or any colored feathers) on crown. COHU ruled out due to rose-pink, not purple feathers on crown, as well as the Tail extending much past wingtips on this bird (they come to approximately same length, if anything wingtips extend past tail on COHU)   I have observed at least 37 individual ANHUs according to my records accross UT, AZ, WA, and now MN. I've observed many RTHU, as well as BHCU, COHU, RUHU, COHU, and BTHU in multiple states. I have not observed ALHU. This ANHU is my first non-RTHU hummingbird observed in MN.  I observed the bird three times for about one minute each between 1:14pm and 2:05pm on Oct 31. I returned and observed the bird on November 1, and observed the bird quite consistently from 7:48am to 8:42am.  MOURC record #2023-106, vote 7–0

Observation Details: A stocky, big-headed hummer with proportionately short bill, and a smoothly margined large central red gorget patch. An immature male Ruby-throated Hummingbird is rather similar, but usually lacks as large a gorget patch and if so the patch will not be as smoothly margined and typically more basally located. A white supercilium is present, which is usually lacking in Archilochus hummers. The bird has a "vest" with a rather "chickenwire" pattern formed by fairly well developed pale fringes to the flank feathers, a pattern usually not as well developed in an immature Archilochus. The tail appears unforked, unlike an immature male Archilochus. In some of the attached photos, P6 appears much too blunt for a male Archilochus. The lower orbital feathers are not as dark as those of immature male RTHU's, whose dark orbital feathers will become a component of the dark "mask" of an adult. Observed at private address.

Third state record, first county record. First observed by Gerry Brevoort last Wednesday, October 23rd. She initially posted photos on Birding Central Ohio of two different hummingbirds she had in her backyard and then sent Alex more images on Saturday for review which showed a suspiciously dusky-flanked hummingbird with a noticeable dark central spot on the throat. Thankfully the bird was very confiding today and we were able to determine the ID within less than 10 seconds of the bird flying in and landing on the feeder. Huge thank you to Gerry and John for opening their property up for viewers to come and enjoy their special visitor!

Observation Details: Continuing mega found on 10/30 and hosted by Beth Tiller. 2nd record of Anna's Hummingbird for Dakota County.   Immature male hummingbird. Rose-pink gorget and crown feathers sparse but visible. Light gray underparts with green speckles. Irridescent green flanks and slightly more bluish-green back. Green nape. Black wings with slight deep purple undertones. Tail feathers I observed were black, but I did not observe the spread tail as Beth did on 10/30. Tail extended past wingtips. Bill was quite straight and short compared to other hummingbirds I have observed.  RTHU, BCHU, and all Selasphorus sp. that occur in the ABA area are ruled out due to the presence of rose-pink feathers (or any colored feathers) on crown. COHU ruled out due to rose-pink, not purple feathers on crown, as well as the Tail extending much past wingtips on this bird (they come to approximately same length, if anything wingtips extend past tail on COHU)   I have observed at least 37 individual ANHUs according to my records accross UT, AZ, WA, and now MN. I've observed many RTHU, as well as BHCU, COHU, RUHU, COHU, and BTHU in multiple states. I have not observed ALHU. This ANHU is my first non-RTHU hummingbird observed in MN.  I observed the bird three times for about one minute each between 1:14pm and 2:05pm on Oct 31. I returned and observed the bird on November 1, and observed the bird quite consistently from 7:48am to 8:42am.  MOURC record #2023-106, vote 7–0

Observation Details: Female, banded. P84402.Most measurements were in range for Anna's female per Pyle with the exception of wing which was short. However she was molting p10 (more than half grown in ) and beginning p9. This can explain the slightly shorter wing...Some pin feathers remained on head and throat, more so on throat. Bird lacked any rose gorget feathers, 3-4 were darker green and at certain angles appeared to have a hint of bronze-coppery. Flight feathers all fresh except for s6 which was faded brown with some mild wear. Measurements as follows: Wing 44.82 (carefully double-measured), tail 27.3, Culmen 18.45.

A stocky, big-headed hummer with proportionately short bill, and a smoothly margined large central red gorget patch. An immature male Ruby-throated Hummingbird is rather similar, but usually lacks as large a gorget patch and if so the patch will not be as smoothly margined and typically more basally located. A white supercilium is present, which is usually lacking in Archilochus hummers. The bird has a "vest" with a rather "chickenwire" pattern formed by fairly well developed pale fringes to the flank feathers, a pattern usually not as well developed in an immature Archilochus. The tail appears unforked, unlike an immature male Archilochus. In some of the attached photos, P6 appears much too blunt for a male Archilochus. The lower orbital feathers are not as dark as those of immature male RTHU's, whose dark orbital feathers will become a component of the dark "mask" of an adult. Observed at private address.

Observation Details: ***mega Two Anna's hummingbirds showed up on my deck today. One of them fed on a torch lily bloom, the other one, a juv. male, fed from a sugar feeder. I live on Browne's Mountain on the South Hill in Spokane. Bird #1 (first two photos): This was the first time I'd seen this particular bird (I've had four different Anna's this year). It had iridescent feathers down the center of the gorget but none that I could see on the crown. It had the typical light gray torso of an Anna's. As of 9.11.16 (the date of this entry), I've seen this same bird multiple times at my feeders and flowers. Bird #2: This juvenile male has been a regular visitor at my feeders and flowers since late June 2016. He has magenta feathers coming in at the gorget and crown, and a light gray torso with green spots. I've heard him vocalize several times while perched in a tree across from my deck, emitting a scratchy repetitive sound.

Update 7-17-22:   This bird was seen and recorded by Patty Rose 7/17/22 (https://ebird.org/checklist/S115286798).  While she was there it was captured by Gwen Baluss who was there banding Rufous Hummingbirds.  She noted that it seemed non-typical for an immature male Anna's and suggests the possibility of it being a hybrid.   Update 7-21-22:   The following is an update that Patty Rose made in her posting.       "7/18/22 - Gwen reviewed photos and her measurements taken in hand. We both observed that the       undertail coverts were marked, which is characteristic of immature ANHU. I asked about the white line       from eye to chest. Gwen says that although it is a Costa trait, many immature ANHU have it too.       Measurements taken in hand are within the norms for immature ANHU. So on balance it is probably       an immature male ANHU".

Observation Details: General impressions are of a big-headed, short-tailed hummer. White above eye, pale grayish auriculars, and fuscia-colored central gorget spot. Primaries extend just short of the tail, unlike Ruby-throated where the tail is noticeably longer. Width of the primaries consistent at rest.    Attached photo shows the spread tail. Note the shape, pattern and color. R4 & 5 are grayish-green and fade to black, terminating in white tips. R3 has very little white and according to Peterson's Hummingbird guide, this could indicate an immature male. R1 is noticeably narrower but still pretty broad and rounded.

Media notes: Anna's hummingbird, 9.1.16, Spokane, WA
Observation Details: ***mega Two Anna's hummingbirds showed up on my deck today. One of them fed on a torch lily bloom, the other one, a juv. male, fed from a sugar feeder. I live on Browne's Mountain on the South Hill in Spokane. Bird #1 (first two photos): This was the first time I'd seen this particular bird (I've had four different Anna's this year). It had iridescent feathers down the center of the gorget but none that I could see on the crown. It had the typical light gray torso of an Anna's. As of 9.11.16 (the date of this entry), I've seen this same bird multiple times at my feeders and flowers. Bird #2: This juvenile male has been a regular visitor at my feeders and flowers since late June 2016. He has magenta feathers coming in at the gorget and crown, and a light gray torso with green spots. I've heard him vocalize several times while perched in a tree across from my deck, emitting a scratchy repetitive sound.

Observation Details: A female Anna's hummingbird, who visited the feeders and flowers at my home for about a week in mid-June, returned today. She was chased off a feeder by a rufous. My juvenile male Anna's was zipping about and generally going crazy until the female flew away.

The bad news is that we sadly originally had this as a Broad Tailed Hummingbird  which had been reported from the location earlier.  The good news is that the photos show it is instead a male Anna's - also rare (but far less so) in this area.

Observation Details: One of our highest hummingbird counts ever, with the numbers more than doubling since yesterday. About 20-25 always around feeder. For the past week we have had roughly 3ad.m. visiting the feeder. Today that number grew to around 11ad.m. Similarly about 8im.m. (typically the bulk of feeder users at this time, before in about October-December the demographic switches to primarily females) became almost 20im.m. I would say 42 is a conservative estimate. The fact that we have no selasphorus (which we typically have at least 1 of around now, but normally 2 or 3) is mind boggling. Allen's dispersal this year was also very odd--it started a few weeks early and seems to have ended a few weeks early, as well.

Observation Details: A continuing late hummer, first seen by MS and JS over a week ago, and only recently identified as an Anna's Hummingbird, the first modern record for this species in Los Alamos County.  This is a medium-sized hummingbird, larger than a Rufous or Calliope, about the same size as a Broad-tailed, and smaller and chunkier than a Black-chinned.  There is no rufous coloration on the flanks, or in any of the tail feathers, which are tipped in white.  The bill is shorter and less curved than a Black-chinned.  In most presentations, the bill appears completely straight.  The widths of the primary feathers are almost constant from P1 to P10, and the secondaries are squared off to emarginated. The central tail feathers, while still green, are noticeably darker than the outer tail feathers, another characteristic of Anna's.  This bird shows buffy edges to its feathers, noticeable everywhere except on the lower back, suggesting the bird is a hatch-year bird.  I could not discern any grooves on the bill, which would confirm it as a juvenile, but the pictures may not have the resolution needed to make that call.  The emerging gorget pattern of rosy spangles resembles that of an adult female, and there are no incoming spangles on the head or crown (which, had they been present, would suggest immature male). When perched, the bird sometimes shows wings longer than tail, uncharacteristic of female Anna's.  However, it is possible that the bird is in mid-molt and that the tail feathers have not fully grown in. Altogether, these features suggest the bird is a hatch-year female, likely hatched in the January 2022 time frame.  If so, the bird would likely be a stray from the coastal climate of the west coast or Baja California.  Thanks to Mohini Rawool-Sullivan and John Sullivan for locating and identifying this bird.

Media notes: 12.10.16 An overwintering adult male Anna's hummingbird at my feeder in Spokane, WA
Observation Details: An adult male Anna's hummingbird visits the heated feeder on my deck about every 30 minutes throughout most of the day. I believe he sleeps in a bush in my backyard--at least, that's were I saw him retire at dusk one evening, and emerge from at dawn (on a different day). He often drinks from the feeder and then perches there for awhile, usually for a few minutes, but sometimes for as long as 15-20 minutes. I have no flowers anymore. The temperatures in Spokane have been as low as the teens and we've had several inches of snow. This hummingbird has been with me since Oct. 10, although he disappeared for two weeks, from October 28-Nov. 12. I recognized him from numerous images I captured of him.

Media notes: Wing whir and intermittent "Chip" calls of this species. Several males.

NOTES: [The first part contains "Song" (with the first rendition decapitated) followed by a series of sharp "Chip" calls, apparently by a perched bird.  The second part is mostly wing "whirring" but also with chipping (apparently from a second bird in the background).  The third part has only wing whirr, the fourth is mostly wing whirr but with one Chip at the beginning, and the fifth part has primarily softer Chip calls from a flying bird in addition to some wing whirr.  Quality changed from 2-1 to 2-1, 1-2 - CAM - 9 December 2004].

Observation Details: Continuing from earlier this morning. Last seen around 9:45 AM. Appears to be an Anna's Hummingbird according to Jim Pawlicki and Andy Guthrie who checked the photos. There is green flecking on the flanks, grayish tinged underparts and duller green upper parts. The bird is proportionally larger headed and shorter billed than Ruby-throated.

Observation Details: The homeowner, Julie Hatch, reported to our local birding listserv that she had a hummingbird that had been coming to her feeder since late October.  We came to identify it and to help her figure out how to help it survive the winter.  This is the first record of this species in Cache County, in eBird or otherwise.  Viewed on private property with permission from the homeowner.  Coincidentally, this was the last day she saw this bird in her yard, although another birder reported it to eBird the next day. Observation Details: There has been an increase in Anna's  hummingbirds at our feeders the past few day. I can tell the immature males apart by the different colors in the gorget. Some have fully developed gorgets but no red on crown. Others have spotting on gorgets.  The males are identified by rose red crown and throat. The females by the rose red patch on throat and the white behind the eye and the green mottled underparts. The juveniles are told by their shape which is stout and the green spotted mottling on underparts.

Media notes: Anna's hummingbird, 9.1.16, Spokane, WA
Observation Details: ***mega Two Anna's hummingbirds showed up on my deck today. One of them fed on a torch lily bloom, the other one, a juv. male, fed from a sugar feeder. I live on Browne's Mountain on the South Hill in Spokane. Bird #1 (first two photos): This was the first time I'd seen this particular bird (I've had four different Anna's this year). It had iridescent feathers down the center of the gorget but none that I could see on the crown. It had the typical light gray torso of an Anna's. As of 9.11.16 (the date of this entry), I've seen this same bird multiple times at my feeders and flowers. Bird #2: This juvenile male has been a regular visitor at my feeders and flowers since late June 2016. He has magenta feathers coming in at the gorget and crown, and a light gray torso with green spots. I've heard him vocalize several times while perched in a tree across from my deck, emitting a scratchy repetitive sound.

Observation Details: Continuing: Owners of the house where adult male is hanging out (word ave) said there were two hummers the previous day. Later I did photo comparisons and it appears that the juvenile male seen today as a second bird at Word location is also the bird in my yard.  Apparently he can fly faster than I can drive.

Third state record, first county record. First observed by Gerry Brevoort last Wednesday, October 23rd. She initially posted photos on Birding Central Ohio of two different hummingbirds she had in her backyard and then sent Alex more images on Saturday for review which showed a suspiciously dusky-flanked hummingbird with a noticeable dark central spot on the throat. Thankfully the bird was very confiding today and we were able to determine the ID within less than 10 seconds of the bird flying in and landing on the feeder. Huge thank you to Gerry and John for opening their property up for viewers to come and enjoy their special visitor!

Observation Details: Female with active nest in same tree as Bushtit nest. Could also hear displaying male in vicinity. Initially from the trail I could only find tiny gaps in branches through which I could see the nest, but eventually I found a spot off the trail with a great view (unfortunately, right under LEGO nest, so I shot a couple quick photos and got back on the trail to avoid disturbing the LEGOs). Twice I saw the female land on the nest and poke her beak down into it before settling in. I suspect she was just moving eggs around, as I didn't see any little bills sticking up or the kind of shuddering feeding motions I've seen in past years.

photo, looks like female: at feeder 1:20pm then perched: same bird as yesterday  interesting: looking now at my photos - this is the first time I have such good photos of a female hummer to look at - does an Anna's really have such a short bill? the green-gray breastsides are good for Anna's:  one online site says re Costa's female/immature compared to Anna's, "Costa's proportionately longer billed but shorter tailed; Costa's generally plainer on throat and underparts, without dusky throat spotting": so certainly the short-seeming bill and short-seeming wings on this photoed bird today, would NOT indicate Costa's

Viewed for approximately one hour with 10x bins and a 20x scope. Many photos forthcoming. Hummer with emerald green back and head, and light to buffy underneath. White teardrop behind eye noted along with small central gorget spot which popped bright pink in sunlight. Some white tips were seen in retrices. Photos should clearly determine how extensive the white tips were. Bill was relatively short and straight with a hint of down-curve. Preliminary ID is an adult female Anna’s Hummingbird.

Observation Details: The homeowner, Julie Hatch, reported to our local birding listserv that she had a hummingbird that had been coming to her feeder since late October.  We came to identify it and to help her figure out how to help it survive the winter.  This is the first record of this species in Cache County, in eBird or otherwise.  Viewed on private property with permission from the homeowner.  Coincidentally, this was the last day she saw this bird in her yard, although another birder reported it to eBird the next day.    This sighting was also reported in North American Birds 67(1):153-155.  Photographed, by Ryan O'Donnell:

This bird has been present since at least Oct 7, but has been misidentified (by me) as a Black-chinned Hummingbird.  Alerted to the probability of a misidentification, I circulated photos taken over the last 3 weeks.  Also, I have noticed that the bird is molting the primaries, and as a result produces a unique buzzing noise when flying.  The bird's vocalizations have not been consistent with a Black-chinned Hummingbird, but only today did I hear it produce the buzzy chatter call of an Anna's Hummingbird.  Other traits pointing to Anna's (courtesy of Sheri L. Williamson, author of "Hummingbirds of North America") : The robust proportions, proportionally large head, mottled throat and underparts, even widths and "generic" shapes of the primaries, and late primary molt this time of year all point to this ID.

Observation Details: Continuing 2nd state record in the area since at least 11/3.  Seen upon arrival feeding in the blue saliva in the front yard of 1765 Crescent Rd.  When it was not feeding on the flowers it was perched in the red bush near them soaking in the sun, it sat on an exposed perch giving great views for close to a half hour there.  It once went up into the hemlock above the house to hawk for insects and again hawked for them at the top of a tree across the street.  Very faithful to the yard, only leaving our sight for maybe a total of 5 minutes while we were there.  Hopefully this bird will learn to use the two feeders in the yard before it gets too cold and the flowers die.  Photos attached.

Observation Details: Continuing mega found on 10/30 and hosted by Beth Tiller. 2nd record of Anna's Hummingbird for Dakota County.   Immature male hummingbird. Rose-pink gorget and crown feathers sparse but visible. Light gray underparts with green speckles. Irridescent green flanks and slightly more bluish-green back. Green nape. Black wings with slight deep purple undertones. Tail feathers I observed were black, but I did not observe the spread tail as Beth did on 10/30. Tail extended past wingtips. Bill was quite straight and short compared to other hummingbirds I have observed.  RTHU, BCHU, and all Selasphorus sp. that occur in the ABA area are ruled out due to the presence of rose-pink feathers (or any colored feathers) on crown. COHU ruled out due to rose-pink, not purple feathers on crown, as well as the Tail extending much past wingtips on this bird (they come to approximately same length, if anything wingtips extend past tail on COHU)   I have observed at least 37 individual ANHUs according to my records accross UT, AZ, WA, and now MN. I've observed many RTHU, as well as BHCU, COHU, RUHU, COHU, and BTHU in multiple states. I have not observed ALHU. This ANHU is my first non-RTHU hummingbird observed in MN.  I observed the bird three times for about one minute each between 1:14pm and 2:05pm on Oct 31. I returned and observed the bird on November 1, and observed the bird quite consistently from 7:48am to 8:42am.  MOURC record #2023-106, vote 7–0

Observation Details: (Rare filter 10): exact tally, then best est as can for the major feeder house.  — — 30-60 (or more) will log as 35, just at house 310 which has at least 8 nectar feeders. 2:50-3:05p, though looks like dusk bc dark soon-rain weather coming in, hummers flying in and out all directions, multiples everywhere, on feeders, on wires, on shrubs and in trees tikking. Made recordings of some of their tikking concentration.  11 on feeders at once while still loads tikking in/on shrubberies.  Made recording of 6 in one shrub, 4 of them ticking and 1 silent.   Dozens of houses on this street have hummer feeders even multiple feeders, but this is the hotspot. Still others at other spots too.   — — This low filter doesn’t represent how many ANHU now winter in coast and in valley. We have so many ANHU in oregon in winter on westside.

Observation Details: Female, banded. P84402.Most measurements were in range for Anna's female per Pyle with the exception of wing which was short. However she was molting p10 (more than half grown in ) and beginning p9. This can explain the slightly shorter wing...Some pin feathers remained on head and throat, more so on throat. Bird lacked any rose gorget feathers, 3-4 were darker green and at certain angles appeared to have a hint of bronze-coppery. Flight feathers all fresh except for s6 which was faded brown with some mild wear. Measurements as follows: Wing 44.82 (carefully double-measured), tail 27.3, Culmen 18.45.

Observation Details: Very rare* Good year for them in the east and first in bama in 12 years! Banded now and continuing to visit feeders very regularly for a few days. Watched on and off over a dozen times as the bird would come to feeders every 10 to 20 minutes, seeming to sit up behind the house in between visits. Immature male beginning to show pinkish feathers on the crown and around the eyes too. Large hummer, dark green above, pale below with thick, dull, greenish mottled underparts. Great views by a dozen observers and many pics

Observation Details: Continuing: Owners of the house where adult male is hanging out (word ave) said there were two hummers the previous day.  I went to hang out to photograph and see if it was a new Anna's or possibly the one from my yard which is .53 miles as the hummingbird flies away. Waited for a while and watched adult male then the second one showed up. Female or juvenile male like at my house. Took some photos of both.  They interacted but did not chase each off.  While the second was there I drove home to see if my young male was at my house and when I got there he was.  I called people at Word house and they said second one just left. We were pretty sure we had verified a third one in town.  Later I did photo comparisons and it appears that the juvenile male seen today as a second bird at Word location is also the bird in my yard.  Apparently he can fly faster than I can drive.

Third state record, first county record. First observed by Gerry Brevoort last Wednesday, October 23rd. She initially posted photos on Birding Central Ohio of two different hummingbirds she had in her backyard and then sent Alex more images on Saturday for review which showed a suspiciously dusky-flanked hummingbird with a noticeable dark central spot on the throat. Thankfully the bird was very confiding today and we were able to determine the ID within less than 10 seconds of the bird flying in and landing on the feeder. Huge thank you to Gerry and John for opening their property up for viewers to come and enjoy their special visitor!

Observation Details: A stocky, big-headed hummer with proportionately short bill, and a smoothly margined large central red gorget patch. An immature male Ruby-throated Hummingbird is rather similar, but usually lacks as large a gorget patch and if so the patch will not be as smoothly margined and typically more basally located. A white supercilium is present, which is usually lacking in Archilochus hummers. The bird has a "vest" with a rather "chickenwire" pattern formed by fairly well developed pale fringes to the flank feathers, a pattern usually not as well developed in an immature Archilochus. The tail appears unforked, unlike an immature male Archilochus. In some of the attached photos, P6 appears much too blunt for a male Archilochus. The lower orbital feathers are not as dark as those of immature male RTHU's, whose dark orbital feathers will become a component of the dark "mask" of an adult. Observed at private address.

Observation Details: Continuing bird. Photos. Banded. Got there at 11:30am. First visit was at 12:30. Then 12:43, 12:48 and 1:20. I left at 1:30.

I believe this is the bird that was earlier called an Anna's x Costa's hybrid.  I think that claim is retracted.   The bird does show some purplish tints in the gorget and head feathers, but that can be an effect of light.  The outer gorget feathers are long, but not too long to be an Anna's.  The structural feature that clinches this as an Anna's is the long tail as compared to the wings.  The wings fall well short of the tail tip.

Observation Details: A lifer for me! Quite a rare species at this point in Alaska. As I recall, this might have been the only one being seen in the state this winter...? Either an adult female or young male. Additional notes: "The hummingbird was first seen around 10:30AM and was seen in the Salmonberry bushes right behind the house. The bird then fed at the feeder at least 3 times in the next half hour. Every time it came to the feeder, it called. Even with my standing 6ft away from the feeder it didn't bother it. The bird was observed at the house on the corner of 3rd St. and Adams once. They also had two hummingbird feeders up."

Bird first sighted Oct 7. Traits pointing to Anna's (courtesy of Sheri L. Williamson, author of "Hummingbirds of North America") : The robust proportions, proportionally large head, mottled throat and underparts, even widths and "generic" shapes of the primaries, and late primary molt this time of year all point to this ID.
